Requirement:
===========
- Qt 4.1.x or higher (http://www.trolltech.com)
- libchipcard 2.1.4 or higher (http://www.libchipcard.com)
- gwenhywfar-2.2.0 or higher (http://gwenhywfar.sf.net/)

Installation for Linux user:
====================
- install Qt 4.1.x (have you another distribuiton as SuSE, Mandrake, RedHat, Debian, Gentoo, get the source package of Qt 4.1.x and compile self)
- install gwenhywfar 2.2.0
        ./configure --prefix=/usr && make && su -c "make install"
- then install libchipcard 2.1.4
        ./configure --prefix=/usr && make && su -c "make install"

- extract qcardreader-0.0.1.tar.gz
- open a shell console (like: konsole)
- go into folder, where is your exctraced tar archive
- enter the follow comand: qmake && make
- if compile complet without error, no errors might emerge :-) go to sub folder bin and enter the following command: ./qrc
- it is not make install requirement

Installation for Windows user:
====================
- install Qt 4.1.x 
- install gwenhywfar 2.2.0
- then install libchipcard 2.1.4

- extract qcardreader-0.0.1.tar.gz
- open a shell console (Start->Execute (Ausführen)->cmd and press enter)
- go into folder, where is your exctraced tar archive
- enter the follow comand:
        qmake
        nmake or mingw32-make
- if compile complet without error, no errors might emerge :-) go to sub folder bin and enter the following command: ./qrc
- or you use the precompiled binary (it is the easiest way)

that is it, have fun ;-)

